# This is a usage file for the VM script
# It provides information on how to use the script and its options.

Usage: ./vm_script.sh [-g] [-r] [-v] <integer>
Options:
  -g    Generate Vagrantfile based on the specified integer.
  -r    Reset: Delete any generated or copied files from earlier Vagrant provisioning.
  -v    Run `vagrant up` or `vagrant up --provision`.
  <integer>   Step number for Vagrantfile generation.
--
Usage examples:
  ./vm_script.sh -g <integer>    # Generate Vagrantfile based on the specified integer.
  ./vm_script.sh -r              # Reset: Delete any file generated or copied in earlier Vagrant provisioning.
  ./vm_script.sh -r <integer>    # Reset and generate Vagrantfile based on the specified integer.
  ./vm_script.sh -v <integer>    # Generate Vagrantfile based on the specified integer then run `vagrant up`.
  ./vm_script.sh -gr <integer>   # Reset and generate Vagrantfile based on the specified integer.
  ./vm_script.sh -gv <integer>   # Generate Vagrantfile based on the specified integer then run `vagrant up`.
  ./vm_script.sh -rv <integer>   # Reset and generate Vagrantfile based on the specified integer then run `vagrant up`.
  ./vm_script.sh -grv <integer>  # Reset and generate Vagrantfile based on the specified integer then run `vagrant up`.

  -g is implied any time an integer argument is given, so only serves as
     'syntactic sugar' to make the intended use of './vm' explicitly clear.
  -g & -v are both invalid with a valid integer argument.
